==> Diamond problem.
class A {
    void show() { System.out.println("A"); }
}

class B extends A {
    void show() { System.out.println("B"); }
}

class C extends A {
    void show() { System.out.println("C"); }
}

// If Java allowed this:
class D extends B, C { } // ❌ Not allowed
D obj = new D();
obj.show(); // ❓ B’s version or C’s version?
Ambiguity arises. Java can't resolve which show() to call. This is called the diamond problem.